Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the codebase. Let me design the detailed implementation plan.

---

## Implementation Plan: Custom Theme System for T3 Code Editor

### 1. Architectural Design Decisions

**Q1: How should the named theme system coexist with the existing light/dark/system toggle?**

The existing `useTheme` hook manages the light/dark/system *mode* -- this controls whether the `.dark` class is applied to the HTML element, which activates the `@variant dark` CSS block. The new named theme system operates at a different level: it overrides the specific CSS custom property *values* within each mode. The two systems should be **layered**, not merged. The light/dark/system toggle remains unchanged. Each named theme defines color values for *both* light and dark modes. When a named theme is active, its CSS custom properties override the defaults from `index.css` by being set directly on `document.documentElement.style`.

**Q2: Should the theme hook replace or wrap the existing `useTheme`?**

Neither. Create a new, separate `useColorTheme` hook following the same `useSyncExternalStore` pattern. The existing `useTheme` (light/dark/system mode) remains untouched. The settings page uses both hooks independently. This avoids breaking the 5 existing consumers of `useTheme` (`ChatMarkdown.tsx`, `DiffPanel.tsx`, `ChatView.tsx`, `DiffWorkerPoolProvider.tsx`, `_chat.settings.tsx`), which all rely on `resolvedTheme` for diff theme resolution and icon theming.

**Q3: How to apply theme colors as CSS custom properties while keeping Tailwind integration working?**

The `@theme inline` block in `index.css` maps Tailwind colors to semantic tokens (e.g., `--color-background: var(--background)`). The semantic tokens like `--background` are defined in `:root` and `@variant dark`. To override them, set them directly on `document.documentElement.style` (inline styles). Inline styles on `:root` have the highest specificity and will override the stylesheet-defined values. When the "default" theme is selected, clear all inline style overrides so the original CSS takes effect. This ensures Tailwind classes like `bg-background`, `text-foreground` etc. automatically pick up the themed values through the existing `var()` chain.

**Q4: Where should the theme selector component live?**

In the existing Appearance section of the settings page (`_chat.settings.tsx`). Add a "Color Theme" subsection below the existing light/dark/system radio group. No standalone component is needed for the initial implementation.

**Q5: What colors should each theme define?**

Each theme must define values for the full set of semantic tokens that appear in `:root` and `@variant dark` in `index.css`. The theme definition in `packages/shared` will store two sets of overrides: one for light mode and one for dark mode. Each set maps token names (like `background`, `foreground`, `primary`, etc.) to CSS color strings.

---

### 2. File-by-File Implementation

#### Step 1: Create `packages/shared/src/themes.ts`

This file defines the pure data types and built-in theme catalog. No browser or React dependencies.

```typescript
/**
 * Semantic color token names that map to CSS custom properties.
 * Each corresponds to `--<token>` in the app's CSS.
 */
export type ThemeColorToken =
  | "background"
  | "foreground"
  | "card"
  | "card-foreground"
  | "popover"
  | "popover-foreground"
  | "primary"
  | "primary-foreground"
  | "secondary"
  | "secondary-foreground"
  | "muted"
  | "muted-foreground"
  | "accent"
  | "accent-foreground"
  | "destructive"
  | "destructive-foreground"
  | "border"
  | "input"
  | "ring"
  | "info"
  | "info-foreground"
  | "success"
  | "success-foreground"
  | "warning"
  | "warning-foreground";

/**
 * A partial map of color token overrides. Only tokens present in this
 * record will be overridden; absent tokens fall back to index.css defaults.
 */
export type ThemeColorOverrides = Partial<Record<ThemeColorToken, string>>;

export interface ThemeDefinition {
  /** Unique stable identifier, e.g. "t3-dark" */
  readonly id: string;
  /** Human-readable display name */
  readonly name: string;
  /** Optional description shown in the UI */
  readonly description?: string;
  /** Color overrides applied when resolvedTheme is "light" */
  readonly light: ThemeColorOverrides;
  /** Color overrides applied when resolvedTheme is "dark" */
  readonly dark: ThemeColorOverrides;
  /**
   * Preview swatch colors for the theme selector UI.
   * These are a curated subset used for visual identification.
   */
  readonly preview: {
    readonly background: string;
    readonly foreground: string;
    readonly primary: string;
    readonly accent: string;
  };
}
```

The "default" theme has id `"default"` and *empty* override maps. This signals "use the CSS-defined values from index.css as-is."

The three required themes:
- `"default"` -- empty overrides, preserves the stock index.css colors (this is what the current app uses; the requirement's "t3-dark"/"t3-light" are effectively the existing dark/light modes)
- `"t3-midnight"` -- a deep blue-black dark theme with different accent colors  
- `"t3-sunset"` -- a warm-toned alternative (or the third theme could be "t3-forest", "t3-nord", etc.)

However, re-reading the requirements more carefully, the spec asks for "t3-dark" (default), "t3-light", and "t3-midnight" as named themes. This means:
- `"t3-dark"` maps to "the default dark mode appearance" -- this would have empty overrides (index.css dark values are the default).
- `"t3-light"` maps to "the default light mode appearance" -- also empty overrides (index.css light values are the default).

This creates a problem: "t3-dark" and "t3-light" are not truly separate themes -- they are the existing mode toggle. To make the named themes meaningful while also coexisting with the mode toggle, the cleanest approach is:

- The `"default"` theme means "use stock index.css colors" in whichever mode is active. This is the default.
- `"t3-midnight"` provides dark overrides that differ from stock dark (deeper blacks, blue-shifted accents). Its light overrides can be empty (or also specialized).
- A third theme like `"t3-warm"` or `"t3-aurora"` provides a distinct color palette.

To satisfy the literal requirement naming, I will define:
- `"t3-dark"` with id `"t3-dark"` -- the default, no overrides. Name: "T3 Dark (Default)".
- `"t3-light"` with id `"t3-light"` -- no overrides. Name: "T3 Light (Default)". 
- `"t3-midnight"` with id `"t3-midnight"` -- actual color overrides. Name: "Midnight".

But this is awkward because t3-dark and t3-light are really the same "default" theme just in different modes. A better interpretation: each theme ID defines a complete color palette that works in the current mode (light or dark as determined by the existing toggle). The t3-dark theme is the default dark palette. t3-light is the default light palette. t3-midnight is an alternative dark palette. But the mode toggle already switches between light/dark CSS...

The simplest and most coherent design: **each named theme provides override values for both light and dark mode**. The mode toggle picks which set of overrides to apply. This way:
- Theme "t3-dark" (id: `"default"`) = no overrides, stock index.css values in both modes.
- Theme "t3-midnight" = overrides for dark mode (deep blue-black palette), possibly different light overrides too.
- Theme "t3-sunset" (or third name) = warm-toned overrides for both modes.

Given the requirement literally says "t3-dark", "t3-light", "t3-midnight", I will implement them as:
